nRed: TIRE. ens sste sus ranshn TRE RAI 3\nauvovsicnscssnmsntnanasnns\nRIBS\u2014\n5\nAERO TTR\nped\n*Sells cents per share.\nReserve fund\u2014\nBALTIMORE GRAIN MARKET.\nBaltimore, March 5.\u2014Following are the official\nprices to-day:\nWHEAT--Stock in elevators, 394535 bushels. West\nern spot, March, 99%; April, 1.00%. Contract spot,\nMarch, 993%; April, 1.00%; May, 1.01%.\nCORN~\u2014Stock in elevators, 2,522.82% bushels. Track\nyellow com for domestic delivery at 66%a67 for car\nlots prime on spot. Contract, April, 61%a6ils.\nWestern spot, March, \u20ac3%a63%; April, 64%5a64%\nMar, 6%.\nFWA $22,600.34 32!\nGold certificates. J PA 37,818.3\nTa.\nOATS-Stock in elevators, 138749 bushels; ship\nments from jclevators, 8812. White, No. 2, heavy,\n5%%ab0; do., No. 2. light to medium, 58a58%; do.,\nNo. 3, heavy, 58%a$: do., No. 3, medium, Bass;\ndo.. Ne. 3, light, 5Tasl%: No, 4, light to heavy,\n56a56'2; mixed, No. 2, 57asi%; do., No. 3, 55%a%;\nNo. 4, 54a3.\nRYE\u2014Stock in clevators, 13442 bushels: ship\nments from elevators, 5272 No. 3 Western rye\nquoted at 84a85.\nLIVE STOCK MARKET.\nNew York, March 5. \u2014CATTLE\u2014Recripts, 40.\nBeef slow at 7a per pound, for native sides\nLondon and Liverpool cables unchanged. 8hip\nments to-day were 915 beeves, 1.010 sheep, and\n8,450 quarters of beef; mone to-morrow,\nCALVES\u2014Receipts, 208. Market steady. Common\nto fair veals sold 5.00a8.50. Western calves, 4.12%a\n4.5.\nSHEED\" AND LAMBS-\u2014Receipts, 50. Lambs,\nslow. Choice State lambs, 77 pounds average, 7.75\nper 100 pounds. An extra car at 7.85. No sales of\ncommon or medium lambe\nHOGS\u2014Receipts, 2,780, Feeling, nominally steady.\nChicago, March 5. \u2014CATTLE-Receipts, 6,500. Mar\nket steady to 10 cents higher. Prime beeves, 5.30a6.10;\npoor to medium, 4.2005.20; stockers and feeders,\n3.5025.00; cows and heifers, 2.90a5.00; canners, 1.90\n2.70; Texans, 4.10a5.00.\nHOGS\u2014Recripts, 35.000. Market 5c lower.\n1.1504.45; rough, 4.15a4.25; mixed, 4.2004.47%; heavy,\n4.3024.50; pigs, 3.70a4.20.\nSHEEP\u2019 -Receopts, 12,000. Market, steady to 10e\nhigher. Native sheep, 3.55.9; Western sheep,\n2505.36: native lambs, 5.50a7.00; Western lambs,\nCURB MARKET.\nMISCELLANEOUS BONDS,\nMINING STOCKS,\nWALL STREET NOTES\nw\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\nER Oh\nOil Business as Barometer\nShows Improvement.\n$1,000 at 10.\nMetropolitan Railroad 5g, $1,900 at 108,\nCapital Traction, 5 at 119, 3 at 119%.\n65%. 5 at 69%.\nMergenthaler, 5 at 194,\nLincoln National Bank, 10 at 135.\nRUMOR MILL IS KEPT BUSY\ni'mion Pacific Stories to Sault Every\nPaste Can Be Found in the Street.\nFour Per Cent Cenvertibles Show\nWeakness and Others Bearish ia\nSympathy-~Stagnation on Change.\nNew York, March 5.\u2014The business of\nthe lubricating oil department of the\nStandard Oil Company is a fair barom\neter of the general business of the coun\ntry. Just at present it shows improve\nment. The railways are using more of\nthe commodity, but the principal Increase\nin demand comes from the industrial con\ncerns. The rssumption of mining opera\ntions at Butte has, of course, been re\nflected, but does not by any means ac\ncount for the bulk of the gain.\nWith the exception of the Pacific Coast,\nthe whole country is represented in the\nheavier orders. This meang that the ef\nfects of the depression are passing away.\nIt will be some time before th\u00e9 change\nis reflected in the earnings of the rail\nroads as published from. month to month,\nbut that it is coming the lubricating oil\ndepartment of the Standard Oil Company\ncan see quite plainly. To this depart\nment of the business of the \u201coil trust,\u201d\nthen, all will be willing to wish ged\nspeed.\nThe Standard Oil party used to make\nthe wheels of the stock market go around\nat a lively clip years ago at times when\ntheir company was supplying great quan\ntities of oil to make the wheels of in\ndustry move smoothly. A few brokers\nare living in hopes that they may do it\nagain,\nStories about Union Pacific of a kind\nto suit every taste can be found in the\nstreet. In one place the talk is all about\nthe rich insiders who have sold out, and\nin another place about the rich outsiders\nwho bought in. There are reports of bor\nrowing and maturing loans, of unsatisfac\ntory earnings, of litigation, dividend re\nductions, and other contingencies not a\nwhit more cheerful, and then in other\nquarters assertions are made that the\ncompany is in no urgent need of money,\nand that when the issue of new securi\nties is actually made it wili be backed by\nthe greatest banking combination that\nhas ever backed any issue \u2018of American\nrailroad securities, But to neither the\nfavorable nor the unfavorable reports\ndoes the stock respond to any large ex\ntent, and some traders, observing this,\nhave recently been scalping profits in it\nby buying it for a turn when it declines\na point or two and selling it short on ad\nvances of about similar proportions.\n\n\nWhat has probably been as influential\nas anything else in keeping sentiment\nbearish on Union Pacific is the weakness\nin the bonds, especially the 4 per cent\nconvertibles. In explanatien of this it\nhas been suggested that the weakness in\nthe convertibles is due to the faet that\na mortgage bond on the unmortgaged\nmileage would rank ahead of them, and\nthat the heaviness of the first mortgage\n4s resuits from selling by holders who\nintend to subscribe for the new issue\nwhich they expect to get on pretty fav\norable terms.\n\nHigh, Low Cl\n10.8 10.73\n0.17 10.6\nA new record of inactivity for the pres\nent year was made by the hour between\n1 and 2 o'clock, when the volume of\ntransactions was less than 14,000 shares,\nThe previous low record for the present\nperiod of stagnation was about 18,000,\nwhich, however, was repeated three or\nfour times. Brokers were inclined to be\nlieve that the new low record now estab\nlished was likely to remain a record for\na long time to come.\n\n\nQuotations furnished by E. F. Hutton Co.,\nof the New York Stock Exchange and the\nicago Board of Trade, Gi. Bowie Chipman, mana\n131 F street northwest,\nChicago, March 5.\u2014Wheat was dull, and with a\nrallies very weak. Cables were unexpectedly\nparticularly from Liverpool, mt had no effect\nsentiment. There was some selling in the after\nrumors of a bank failure in Rio, but this\nlater said to be a small affair and not of\nportance.\non\n\nCorn was firm, notwithstanding the weakness in\nwheat. The market sold up rather easily during the\nmoming on poor grading and continued bad weather\nWest, later reacting with wheat.\nOats were fairly steady, although easing off some\nin the afternoon. Trade was narrow and rather fea\ntureless.\nProvisions were quiet early, advancing sharply dur\nthe middle of the day, with reported liberal buy\nby Armour brokers.\nih\n#Es\nqs\nCH\n1 TIRIRE, PO wes C000\nLow. Close.\naig\nATRRRE mm mas ms wis\naga\nSeptember........... 9%\nCORN~\nWie\nBRAN... nous nuns paar 63\n2 821% 627%\npL ER es TE 61\nOATS\n61% Bil\n607s 50%\n5 RR FE 53%\nB34 53\nSR nisms iamemin sans 5%\n45% H%\nPORK\nMAY... cs cosnsssnsinee 91.85\nJul\u00a5e.o ee ERRORS\nLARD\n12.02 1.8\n12.8 12.17\nSk\nhea 328 =8%\nhen By KEM\nLe\n1%\n7.75\n7.9%\nMay. TAURINE 7.22 7.87\nSTR JOR 4. 8.02 hf\n6.70\n6.97\nRi din snsssrnniusinss BBS 6.7 6.8)\noom\nNew York, March 5. \u2014WHEAT Weaker; fairly\nactive. No. 1 Northern Duluth, to arrive, 1.19%;\nNo. 2 red, f. 0.'b, 108%; No. 2 hard, f. 0. bh,\n115%: No. 1 marareni, f. 0 b., 1.04%; No. 2 maca\nroni. 1.01%. Exporters took twenty loads.\nCORN-\u2014Steady;: slow trade. No. 2 elevator, 71:\nnew, No. 2, f. 0. b., 64%, for February to March;\nNo. 2 white, f. 0. b., 65; No. 2 yellow, f. o. b., 65.\nof a nominal; smal: supply. No. 2 f. o\nb., 89.\nPrices of futures follow:\nIcsts\nWHEAT- Open. High. Low. Close. Cleso.\nMay LOK 1.07 1.05% 1067-16 1.08%\nuly... 1.02 1.0% 10 1.01% 1.01%\nCORN\u2014\nBARE 7 conan criana ns eanen.  manias n%\nJuly