eling here was mixed.\nOre big operator, it is estimated, sold about 20,00\nbales yesterday, but some papers claim he denfed it.\nThe national ginners\u2019 official report showed 10,916,000\nbales, but it had no ectect on the market. In.\nterior receipts were heavy Port were\n15,000 bales, against 22.50 on the same\u201d day last\n\n\n\n\nNew York.\nOpen.\nMARR ones ss nnicannsnnanes JES\nLow.\nJOIY  cssnnessinavansnenans JE\nLi SERPITA\n0.\nHigh.\n10.68\n10.83\n10.38\n10.03\nMEY  icninsrstsemsstssnsns 10.80\n10.57\n16.69\n10.46\n9.9\n4\nwBES\nKR\nNew Orleans,\npL A 10.%0\nBEAN aa eent sn pamkanes se amet 10.0\nVL a ORR Ruins 10.69\n10.70 10.80\nNEW YORK PRODUCE.\npacket, 12.0812 30.\nNew York, March 5.\u2014-SUGAR-The local market\nfor raw sugar was strong, with centrifugal, 3 test,\nquoted at 3.89; Muscorado, #0 test, at 328, and mo\nlasses sugar, 89 test, at 314 The last sale was\n217-32 for Cuba sugar, cost and freight terms. Re\nfined sugar was firm, but quiet, and unchanged. The\nLondon market for beet sugar was steady, with\nMarch quoted at 10s 3d and April at 10s 3%d.\n\nNAVAL STORES-The local market for spirits\nturpentine was very weak, with machine-made bar\nreis quoted st 52%. At Savannah the market was\neasy at $8. Rosin was steady and unchanged, with\ncommon to good strained quoted at 3.85. Tar was\nLate in the afternoon it was rumored\nthat the Union Pacific financial plan\nnominal, at 45 for oil barrels,\nBUTTER Receipts, 4,176 packages. Choice steady;\ncreamery extra, 3.\nEGGS Receipts, 8.343 cases. Market higher. Near\nby white, fancy, Z[aZ8; do. mixed, faney, 24al;\nWestern firsts, 25%.\n\nMILL FEED -Firm; fair demand. Spring bran,\n100-pound sacks, to arrive, 21.50; middlings,\ncity bran, 25.50, in bulk; Western red dog, 30.50, to\narrive; winter wheat bran, in 10-pound sacks, 27.85.\n\nOATS Steady; slow trade. No. 3 white, 58; No.\nwhite, 57; No. 2 mixed, 5%.\nFLOUR--Strong; moderate trade. Spring patents,\n5.6006.00; spring clears, 4.80a5.00; winter straights,\n4.50a4.70; winter clears, 4.252445; Kansas, in sacks,\npatents, 5.19a5.25; straights, 4.75a5.00; clear, 4.25a4.65.\n\n\n\nRYE FLOUR-Steady; moderate demand. We\nquote, 4.65a5.25.\n\nCORN MEAL-\u2014-Moderate business. Kiln-dried, for\nexport, 3.25a3.30; coarse meal, in bags, 1.34al.37.\n\nBUCKWHEAT FLOUR-Small trade; light sup\nply. Choice quoted at 3.00.\nHAY-Receipts, 970 tons. Market firm: fair busi\nness. Prime timothy, 1.06; No. 1, 1.00al05; No. 2,\n%0a%;: No. 3. 85.\nSTRAW Steady; fair trade. Long rye, T0aT5.\nBEEF\u2014-Firm;: demand fair. Family, 14.50a15.00;\nPORK\u2014Steady; fair inquiry. Mess, 13.50a14.00;\nfamily, 15.00215.50,\nTALLOW Weaker; moderate trade. City, in hogs\nheads. 5.\nLARD-\u2014-Unchanged. Prime Western, \u00a300; city,\n6.85; refined continent, 8.15; South Americar, 8.75;\nrefined Brazilian, in kegs, 10.00; city stearine, 8%;\noleostearine nominal; New York, Tali; Chicago, 7%.\n\nLOCAL PRODUCE MARKET.\nProduce moved wel! on the wholesale market ves.\nterday. Arrivals were liberal, the demand good, and\npractically no change .a prices. Eggs, which have\nbeen weak for a dav or so, steadied up a bit yes\nterday, though there vas no change in the quota\ntions. Poultry, especially i. keys, is higher. Dressed\nmeats, vegetables, and fruit remain dnl,\n(Prices quoted are wholesale)\nBUTTER (Creamery, fancy, 32%a33; do., Wester\nfirsts, 31232; do., seconds, %a28; process fancy, 25a26;\ndo.. fair to good. 2223; dairy, choice, 13a2); good,\n18a19; store-packed, fresh, 16al8.\nCHEESE\u2014Market firm and active on all kinds\nNew York State factory, large, 18al6%; do., fats,\n16%al7; do.. small, 16%al7; do., summer, Jage, 1415:\ndo., summer, small, l4al#%s; do., fair to good, 12al3;\nWestern, factory, new, choice, 1#4ald; do., fair to\ngood. 11; Virginia, 10.\nEGGS\u2014 Nearby fresh Virginia, loss off, 2421: aver\nage, 2: West Virginia and Southwest Virginia, 20.\nTennessee, 2: North Carolina, 19; duck, 30.\nLIVE POULTRY~Chickens, fancy, 15aif; average,\n15; hens, 13al3%; roosters, 7; ducks. large, 13al4; do.\nsmall, 11al2; geese, 8al0; turkeys, toms, per Ib., 14a\n15; do., hens, 16al7; do., thin, 10; keats, 10.\nDRESSED POULTRY-Turkeys, hens, undrawn,\nper lb, 18al9; do.,, average, undrawn, Tals; do.\nthin, 10212; oid toms, 15al6; chickens, large, 15a18;\nsmall, 17al8; hens, choice, 13al4; roosters, 8; ducks,\nold, 13al5; geese, 10al2; capons, 7-1b. average, 1s;\nsmall, 15216.\nDRESSED MEATS Calves, full dressed, 8a10.\nheads off, 8; hog-dresseC calves, 729; hams, country,\nsugar-cured, 13al5; hogs, small and neat, per ewe,\n6.0006.50; do., medium, 6.00; do., heavy, 5.5028.00,\nGAME\u2014Quail per dozen, 2.50a2.75; do., small, 1.5\n22.00; opossums, each, 2adl.\nVEGETABLES--Potatoes, home-grown. per bushel,\n70a75; do., rural, 70a75; sweet potatoes, per bbl, 3.50\n2d.00; yams, 2.00a2.50; cabbage, per cwt., \u00a70a%:\nper 2\n2.00a2.25; lettuce, per basket\nLS.\nGREEN FRUITS\u2014Apples, York Imperial, per bbl.\n2253.00; Ben Davis, 200a25\u00a2; Wine Sap, 225a3.00\nAltemarle Pippin, 3.06a4.00; fancy table fruit, 3.5\n24.00; Spy, 2.50a3.25; loose packad, 1.00al.50. Oranges,\nFlorida, bright, per box, 1.25al.75; do., russets, 2.25\n2.75; California navels, 2.25a2.50. Grape fruit, Fior\n2.50; do., per bbl,, 5.00a8.06.\nDRIED FRUITS\u2014Apptes, sliced, fancy, 8a7; do.\nsliced, bright, \u20acas.\nSUNDR 2; taliow, 5; honey, whits\nclover, Flb. wew, 13; do., 2b. new, 10al2: ginseng\nper ib. 5 per 1b., 40: Golden Seal,\nads; Pink, 12al4; 223; Spake Root, 35;\nwalnut 12al4.\nLOCAL FINANCIAL GOSSIP.\nTrading on the Washington Stock Ex\nchange yesterday switched off to invest\n\u2018ment buying of bonds, Capital Traction\n58 and other railroad bonds being the fa\nvorites. There was some call for Wash\nington Railway and Electric 4s, which,\nafter sales of $3,000 on regular call and\n$500 more after call, exhausted the se\ncurities offered. More of this issue\n\u2018would have been taken if they had been\nforthcoming.\nAbout 140 shares of stock were sold,\n\u2018mostly in fractional lots. The surprise\n\u2018of the day was the closing of a bid on 10\nshares of Lincoln bank stock at 125, the\nbid price for several days past. The\nprice of Washington Railway and Elec\ntric preferred was on an ascending scale\non sales of semething over 100 shares, the\nbest price being for 17 shares at T0%.\nThe market generally is dull, with lit\ntle buying power, beyond a limited num\nber of shares from day to day, which\nseem 10 be taken largely for investment\npurposes, the speculative feature of the\nmarket being practically eliminated,\nCapital Traction 5e, $00 at 100%, $500 at 110,\nWashington Railway and Electric 4s, $3.000 at 75%.\nWashington Rzilway and Electric preferred, 3 at\nAfter eall-Metropolitan Railroad 5s, $1,000 at 108,\nWashington Railway and Electric 4s, 500 at 76%.\nWashirzton Railway and Electric preferred. 25 at\nCOMMENT ON MARKET.\nBenjamin Woodruff, of Lewis Johnson\nCo.\u2014\"Again the stock market was so\nfeatureless that it is hard to find any\nthing in it to comment upon, transactions\nbeing almost nominal and limitr\u00e9 largely\nto professionals. There were nc announce\nments of importance, but the general\nfeeling seems to be that business is im\nproving. The stock market is, in my\nopinion, largely dependent now upon polit\nical developments. Every one admits that\nprices are cheap enough, provided this\nperiod of uncertainty Is of moderate\nduration. On the other lL.-.nd, if we are\nto have four years more of antagonism\nto business interests and the constant\npromulgation of ideas which will render\nany new enterprise an impossibility,\nit simply must mean receiverships and\none of those periods of protracted read\njustment, such as the country used to\nexperience twenty and thirty years ago.\u201d\nG. Bowie Chipman, of E. F. Hutton\nCo.\u2014\"\"Some little bull tajk over night on\nthe Hill stocks was responsible for further\nshort covering this morning, and it was\nnoticeable that a better feeling prevailed\non the market outlook for the future. The\ncauses for this change of sentiment are\nquite unexplained, as there is little evi\ndence of any change for the better in the\npolitical or business situation. Market\nwise, all T can say is that stocks fail to\nrespond to bad news, and the weakness\nin Union Pacific recently is not showing\nitself to be a factor now, hence it would\nappear that stocks were a better purchase\non weakness than a sale on rallies; how\never, I doubt whether the market Sill\nshow any great betterment, other than\na hardening tendency in stocks, in view\nof the agitation against speculation by\n\u2018the government. The outlook for rail\nroads is gloomy enough with present\nearnings. and there are other bad features\nin the situation; but if bankers are ready\nTITLE INSURANCE STOCKS.\nColumbia Title...... FPR \u00abes\nWashington Market. Banhashases MA. weens\n\n\nfor a moderate improvement in stocks, the\nmarket will go up.\u201d\nHE THREW AWAY HIS MONEY\nThen Told the Police He Had Reen\nRobbed of $165.\nDe Akers Was Distributing Twenty\ndollar Bilis to Street Gamins.\nOnly Forty Dellars Recovered.\n\nWilliam C. De Akers, of 149 Monroe\nstreet, Brooklyn, N, Y. a guest at the\nRiggs House, reported to the police yes\nterday he had been robbed of $I late\nWednesday night,\n\n\nAn investigation by Central Office De\ntectives Weedon and Burlingame showed\nthat De Akers, efter dining well, stood\non Pennsylvania venue, near Fourteenth\nstreet, and tossed twenty-dollar bills into\nthe street for the fun \u00a2f watching a\ncrowd of street gaming fight for the\nmoney.\n\nDe Akers came to Washington Wed\nnesday morning, after a lengthy stay in\nthe West, and started out to celebrate\nhis return to the East in a fitting man\nner. In the course of the celebration\nPennsylvania avenue was strewn with\ntwenty-dollar notes.\n\nOver a hundred dollars was iost in this\nmanner, when a member of the Y. M. C.\nA, took the stranger in tow and piloted\nhim to his hotel. He took $i from the\nBrooklynite and gave it to the hotel\nclerk. This was all of the $155 recovered.\ni\nTAXIMETERS FOR CABS.\nSystem to Be Installed in a Month or\nSo in Washington.\nImproved regulations to govern public\nvehicles is recommended by the Board of\nTrade in several letters to the Cemmis\nsioners.\nThe committee on public order of the\n\u2018Board of Trade recommends that the\nregulations require each public hack to\nbe equipped with a taximeter in perfect\nworking (order; that regulations be en\nforced requiring that horses, while stand\ning, be either hitched or attended by\nsome one, and regulations be enforced re\nquiring a red light to be displayed on\nstreet obstructions from sunset to day\nlight,\nTaximeter cabs have been considered by\nthe Commissioners for some time. Own\ners of the system in New York have\npromised to install the system in this city\nin month or so.\n\nHELD FOR CHILD'S INJURIES.\nEngineer Lets Baby Slip and Frae\ntares Her Skull.\nCharles H. Cogswell, an engineer, liv\ning in Southwest Washington, was yes\nterday placed under a bond of $2,000 by\nAssistant United States Attorney Ralph\nGiven, to await the outcome of injuries\nto his own child, sald to be caused by\ncarelessness on the father's part. The\nchild is in a serious condition.\n\u201cWitnesses say that Cogswell vas throw\ning his sixteen-months-old child in the\nair and catching it on February 25, and\nallowed the baby to slip through his arms\nto the ground. A fracture of the skull\nresulted. Dr. R. M. Ellyson, of 1535 Eighth\nstreet porthwest, is attending the child,\nand said last night her condition was\nslightly improved.\nKORE Sn DIRE. oo cn inn wah vs nn a aah\nTrain Runs Over and Kills Negro.\nAt 4:07 o'clock yesterday afternoon a\nnegro, later Identified as Peter Wood,\nsixty-five years old, 227 M street south\nwest, was run over and instantly killed\nby a Chesapeake and Ohio southbound ex\npress train at Fourteenth street and\nMaryland avenue southwest. The body\nwas taken to the morgue, where it was\nidentified by Wood's wife. The train was\nin charge of Conductor Sam C. Buster,\nof 207 B street northeast and Engineer\nRobe\u00e9rt Saunders.\nStocks and bonds (market value)\nBills receivable and collateral loans\ni and in hands of\nInterest due and accrued\nNet unpaid claims.........\nReserve as required by law\nAmount and character of business trans\nacted during the year 1907\nCommander Peary te Lecture.\nCommander Robert E. Peary, U. S. N.,\nthe arctic explorer, will give his famous\nlecture, \u2018\u201cNearest the pole,\u201d at the Be\nlasco Theater on Friday afternoon, March\n20, at 4:40. This lecture will not only\ncover ground already passed over, but\nwill outline briefly the pian for his next\ntrip.\nWhat resolution is better\nI he Road to for your course of life than\nFINANCIAL.\none by which you firmly re\nIndependence Site ats have a\nbank account\u2014save more. If\nyou have never opened an\naccount, do so. Start to-day,\nand then at the end of a year\nof faithful saving and regular\ndepositing see what you've\ngot!\nYou can start an account\nhere with whatever amount\nyou please, from $1.00 up, and\nwe pay you 3 per cent interest,\nHome Savings Bank\n7th and Mass. Ave.\nBRANCHES:\n7thand H Sts. NE. 436 7thSL.S. W,\nUnder Supervision of the U.S. Treasury\nTHE\nWasHINGTON Loan nd TRUST\nCOMPANY\nDIRECTORS:\n\u201charles B. Bailey, Philip Hichborn, N. H. Shea,\nWm. E. Barker, John A. Johnston, Louis P. Shoemaker,\nJohn Cammack, Martin A. Knapp, Thomas W. Smith,\nJohn R. Carmody, John EB. Larner, Ellis Spear,\nAugustus Crane, jr. Wm. A. Mearns, Johz A. Swope,\nJoseph J. Darlington, H. D. Mirick, George Truesdell,\nJames T. DuBois, Watson J. Newton, B. H. Wamer,\nJohn Jor Edson, Theo. W. Noyes, Herry K. Willard,\nA. I. Fardon, Andrew Parker, A. 8S. Worthington.\nJohn A. Hamilton, Samuel L. Phillips,\nCondensed Siatement of Con